#---------------------------------------------------------------------- 
# GROUP POLICY

Q: Group policy to access everything in S3?
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}

Q: Group policy to everything in S3 with read only mode?
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:Get*",
        "s3:List*"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}

Q: Allow everything on a specific bucket?
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "Stmt1361595623860",
      "Action": [
        "s3:*"
      ],
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:s3:::mucls.lynceantech.com"
      ]
    }
  ]
}

#---------------------------------------------------------------------- 
# ARN

Q: 
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/Using_Identifiers.html#Identifiers_ARNs

Q: Group ARN ?
arn:aws:s3:

Q: Principal ARN?
arn:aws:<vendor>:<region>:<namespace>:<relative-id>
* vendor identifies the AWS product (e.g., Amazon SNS) using a namespace.
* region is the region the resource resides in (e.g., us-east-1), if any. (IAM users, groups, and roles do not include a region.)
* namespace is an AWS account ID with no hyphens (e.g., 111122223333).
* relative-id is the portion that identifies the user, group, role, etc.

Q: Principal ARN?
<!-- Everyone (anonymous users) -->
"Principal":"AWS":"*.*" 
<!-- Specific account or accounts -->
"Principal":{"AWS":"arn:aws:iam::123456789012:root" }
"Principal":{"AWS":"123456789012"}
"Principal":{"AWS":["arn:aws:iam::123456789012:root","arn:aws:iam::999999999999:root"]}  
<!-- Individual user -->
"Principal":"AWS":"arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/Username"  
<!-- Specific role -->
"Principal":{"AWS":["arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/MyRole"]}
<!-- Specific service -->
"Principal":{"Service":["ec2.amazonaws.com"]}
<!-- Individual user in S3 -->
"Principal":{"CanonicalUser":"79a59df900b949e55d96a1e698fbacedfd6e09d98eacf8f8d5218e7cd47ef2be"}

#---------------------------------------------------------------------- 
# POLICIES

Sid         - Statement identifier?
Version     - The Version element specifies the access policy language version
id          - The Id element specifies an optional identifier for the policy. The ID is used differently in different services.
Statement   - The Statement element is the main element for a policy. It can include multiple elements.
Effect      - The Effect element is required and specifies whether you want the statement to result in an allow or an explicit deny. Valid values for Effect are Allow and Deny.
Principal   - The Principal element specifies the user, account, service, or other entity that is allowed or denied access to a resource.
NotPrincipal- The NotPrincipal element lets you specify an exception to a list of principals. For example, you can use this to prevent all AWS accounts except a specific account from accessing a resource.
Action      - The Action element describes the type of access that should be allowed or denied (for example, read, write, list, delete, and so on).
NotAction   - The NotAction element lets you specify an exception to a list of actions. 
Resource    - The Resource element specifies the object or objects that the policy covers.
NotResource - The NotResource element lets you specify an exception to a list of resources.
Condition   - The Condition element lets you specify conditions for when a policy is in effect.




